  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How does chamomile promote relaxation?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Chamomile contains apigenin, a flavonoid that binds to benzodiazepine receptors on GABA-A receptors in the brain. This binding enhances GABA (gamma-aminobutyric acid) activity — the brain\'s primary inhibitory neurotransmitter responsible for calming neural activity. Unlike prescription benzodiazepines (which strongly activate these receptors causing sedation), apigenin is a mild, partial agonist that produces gentle relaxation without sedation, impairment, or dependency risk. Chamomile also contains bisabolol and chamazulene — terpenes with anti-inflammatory and smooth muscle relaxant properties that contribute to digestive calm and physical relaxation. The combination of central nervous system calming (apigenin) and peripheral relaxation (bisabolol) explains why chamomile has been the world\'s most popular calming herb for over 5,000 years.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Is chamomile good for anxiety?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical evidence supports chamomile for mild-to-moderate anxiety. A landmark 2009 study in the Journal of Clinical Psychopharmacology found that chamomile extract (220mg/day) significantly reduced anxiety symptoms compared to placebo in patients with generalized anxiety disorder (GAD). A follow-up 2016 study in Phytomedicine confirmed that long-term chamomile supplementation (1,500mg/day for 38 weeks) reduced anxiety relapse rates and improved overall well-being. Chamomile is not a replacement for prescribed anxiolytic medications or therapy for severe anxiety, but it represents an evidence-backed herbal option for mild-to-moderate anxiety and daily stress management. The gentle mechanism (partial GABA-A agonism) means chamomile can be used daily without the tolerance, dependency, or withdrawal risks associated with benzodiazepines.' } },
