  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'What is the best time to take chamomile gummies?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'The best timing depends on your goal: For relaxation and anxiety relief, take chamomile gummies 30-60 minutes before a stressful event (work presentation, social gathering) or as part of an afternoon wind-down routine. For sleep support, take chamomile gummies 30-60 minutes before bedtime to allow apigenin to reach peak blood levels and enhance GABA activity during the sleep transition period. For digestive comfort, take chamomile gummies 30 minutes before meals. Chamomile\'s effects are relatively mild and short-acting (2-4 hours), so timing close to the desired effect window is important. Some people take chamomile twice daily — once in the afternoon for daytime calm and once before bed for sleep support.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'Does chamomile interact with medications?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Chamomile has potential interactions with several medication classes: (1) Blood thinners (warfarin, heparin) — chamomile contains coumarin compounds that may enhance anticoagulant effects. (2) Sedatives and benzodiazepines — additive sedative effects may occur. (3) Cyclosporine and other CYP3A4 substrates — chamomile may inhibit the CYP3A4 enzyme, affecting drug metabolism. (4) Diabetes medications — chamomile may lower blood sugar, potentially enhancing hypoglycemic drug effects. (5) People with ragweed or chrysanthemum allergies may cross-react with chamomile (same Asteraceae plant family). Always inform your healthcare provider about chamomile supplementation, especially if you take prescription medications. Discontinue chamomile 2 weeks before scheduled surgery due to its mild anticoagulant properties.' } },
  { '@type': 'Question', name: 'How much chamomile should I take?', acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: 'Clinical trials have used a range of chamomile doses: The 2009 GAD study used 220mg/day of standardized chamomile extract (1.2% apigenin). The 2016 long-term study used 1,500mg/day of chamomile extract. Traditional tea consumption typically provides 100-200mg of chamomile per cup. Most chamomile gummies provide 200-500mg of chamomile extract per serving. For general relaxation and mild anxiety relief, 200-500mg of standardized chamomile extract daily is a reasonable starting point. For more significant anxiety support, studies suggest 500-1,500mg daily may be needed. Start at the lower end and increase based on response. Look for products standardized to apigenin content (1.2% or higher) for consistent potency.' } },
