    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Chamomile Gummies</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does chamomile promote relaxation?</summary><p>Apigenin (a flavonoid) binds GABA-A benzodiazepine receptors as a mild partial agonist, enhancing inhibitory neurotransmission. Bisabolol relaxes smooth muscle. Together: mental calm + digestive relaxation + physical ease without sedation or dependency.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is chamomile good for anxiety?</summary><p>Clinical trials support chamomile for mild-to-moderate anxiety. A 2009 RCT found 220mg/day significantly reduced GAD symptoms. A 2016 study confirmed 38 weeks of daily use maintained anxiety reduction. Gentle mechanism with no tolerance or dependency.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take chamomile gummies every day?</summary><p>Yes. Safe for daily use up to 38 weeks (the longest clinical trial duration). No tolerance, dependency, or withdrawal observed. Daily use may improve consistency of calming effects. Chamomile has been consumed daily as tea for thousands of years.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best time to take chamomile gummies?</summary><p>For stress: 30-60 minutes before stressful events. For sleep: 30-60 minutes before bed. For digestion: 30 minutes before meals. Effects last 2-4 hours. Can be taken twice daily (afternoon + bedtime) without daytime drowsiness.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does chamomile interact with medications?</summary><p>Potential interactions with blood thinners (coumarin content), sedatives (additive effects), CYP3A4 substrates, and diabetes medications. Ragweed/chrysanthemum allergy cross-reactivity possible. Discontinue 2 weeks before surgery. Always inform your doctor.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much chamomile should I take?</summary><p>200-500mg standardized extract for general relaxation. 500-1,500mg for anxiety support (per clinical trials). Look for products standardized to 1.2%+ apigenin. Start lower and increase based on response. Tea provides approximately 100-200mg per cup.</p></details>

